description.narrative: By 2022, government and partners have institutional capacity to ensure pregnant women, infants and children from marginalized and at risk groups, especially the girl child have equitable availability, access, knowledge and demand for quality health care services for immunization as well as prevention and treatment of other childhood illnesses including pneumonia, diarrhoea, malaria and paediatric HIV, in selected states., which contributes to Child Health, Immunization, Treatment And Care Of Children Living With Hiv. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Harnessing Power Of Business And Markets, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, United Nations Working Together. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Business and Key Business Stakeholders demonstrate growing willingness, commitment and resource allocation for protecting and promoting child rights in policy and practice by 2022

description.narrative: UNICEF continued its support in augmenting immunization coverage with equity focus. More than 116 million children were vaccinated with one-dose of Measles-Rubella (MR) vaccine. Renewed strategy of Intensified-Mission-Indradhanush 2.0 (IMI) launched to reach missed children in 381 low-performing districts. Rotavirus vaccine (RVV) scaled-up in entire country to address the diarrhoea-burden and Tetanus and Diphtheria (Td) vaccine introduced to combat increasing adult diphtheria cases. Households of 100 million under-five children were prepositioned with ORS during pre-peak season through Intensified-Diarrhoea-Control-Fortnight. Renewed efforts towards control of Pneumonia led to updation of antibiotic policy and launching of awareness generation campaign during the peak-winter season. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:10/01/2020
